<BaseLayout title="Easter — Unmasking the Holidays — Nazaryah" description="Easter replaced Passover — the feast Yahushua observed and commanded. Named after a pagan goddess, dated by the spring equinox, filled with fertility symbols.">
  <div class="hol-wrap">
    <section class="hol-hero">
      <p class="hol-series">&#8213; Unmasking the Holidays · Spring &#8213;</p>
      <h1 class="hol-title">Easter</h1>
      <p class="hol-sub">25 Traditions. A pagan goddess's name. The Passover that was replaced.</p>
    </section>
    <section class="hol-section">
      <div class="hol-prose">
        <p>Easter replaced Passover — the very feast Yahushua observed and told His disciples to keep in remembrance of Him (Luke 22:19). The church moved the date from the 14th of Nisan (Yahuah's calendar) to the first Sunday after the first full moon after the spring equinox — a pagan astronomical marker, not a biblical one.</p>
        <p>The 40 days of Lent mirror the 40 days of weeping for Tammuz that Yahuah called an abomination in Ezekiel 8:14. The Easter sunrise service mirrors the sun worship condemned in Ezekiel 8:16. The holiday is named after a dawn/sun goddess (called Eostre in Germanic tradition, Ishtar in Babylon). Its symbols — eggs, rabbits, and the hare — are fertility symbols of the goddess.</p>
        <p>This study examines 25 Easter traditions and reveals how the church replaced Yahuah's Passover with a holiday named after a pagan goddess, dated by the spring equinox, and filled with the symbols of fertility worship.</p>
      </div>
    </section>
    <section class="hol-coming">
      <div class="hol-coming-inner">
        <div class="hol-coming-icon">&#9685;</div>
        <h2 class="hol-coming-title">Full Study Coming</h2>
        <p>This study is being assembled. Return to the <a href="/holidays" class="hol-link">Holidays hub</a> or explore <a href="/sun-worship/sacred-act" class="hol-link">The Sacred Act</a> while this page is built.</p>
      </div>
    </section>
    <div class="hol-nav">
